                <note rend="inline" type="source">662.6331/73: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Belgium</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gibson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-03-30T13:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 30, 1931—1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>15. Embassy’s 19, March 28, 5 p.m. We are satisfied from your wire that no
                    Government claimed the advantages of the Belgo-Luxemburg Economic Union under
                    the most-favored-nation clause in treaties with either country. You are to
                    ascertain for us, however, whether or not in 1921 either Belgium or Luxemburg
                    was a party to any commercial treaty which contained an unconditional
                    most-favored-nation clause. We desire an immediate reply.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
